 for bestpractices and # Drilldown — Why Did This Move?

## Overview
This prompt instructs an AI development tool to build the “Drilldown — Why Did This Move?” experience within the Gbox360 Investor Perception Index & Narrative Intelligence product. The goal is to provide a detailed, actionable spec for a page that explains a selected narrative or IPI movement, surfaces underlying NarrativeEvents with raw payloads, authority/credibility signals, timestamps, and a replayable chronological view. It also wires into a Drilldown & Traceability UI and an Audit Export & Artifact Generation flow, and it ties from the Company View (IPI Detail) to this drill-down view. All code must be resilient to null/undefined values and follow runtime-safety rules described in the project context.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A dedicated Drilldown — Why Did This Move? page that renders a detailed explanation for the currently selected narrative or IPI movement. It lists the NarrativeEvents that contributed to the movement, displays raw payload viewing, authority/credibility signals, precise timestamps, and provides a replayable chronological view of events.

Goals:
- Deliver a transparent, auditable narrative explanation for a given IPI movement.
- Surface the exact sequence of NarrativeEvents that drove the movement, with provenance, weights, and inputs used in calculations.
- Allow users to inspect raw payloads, replay timelines, and export signed audit artifacts (JSON + PDF) for governance, compliance, and investor decision purposes.

Connected features:
- Drilldown & Traceability UI: An interactive UI to inspect narratives, list NarrativeEvents, view raw payloads, replay timelines, and export audit artifacts.
- Audit Export & Artifact Generation: Create signed, exportable artifacts (JSON + human-readable PDF) including raw payload references, event lists, weighting parameters, and calculation inputs used for the given IPI view.
- Back to Company View: A navigation control to return to the Company View (IPI Detail) with the selected company context and the current IPI state.

UI elements and how they need to look:
- Narrative Header: Title of the narrative, current persistence score, contribution amount, and trend indicator.
- Events List: Paginated, append-only list of NarrativeEvents showing source tag, speaker entity/role heuristic, audience class, timestamp, a snippet of the event, authority score, credibility proxy flags, and a “view raw” button.
- Raw Payload Modal: A modal that shows the complete original payload JSON/text, with provenance metadata and a download option.
- Replay / Timeline Controls: Play, back, forward controls to step through the timeline of NarrativeEvents; highlight repetitions and spikes; optional loop/repeat for continuous replay.
- Filters: Source type (news/social/transcript), authority tier (Analyst/Media/Retail), credibility flags, and a custom time-range picker.
- Audit Export Button: Exports filtered events and narrative summary as a signed artifact (JSON + PDF).
- Back to Company View Link: A link or button to navigate back to the Company View while preserving context.
- Visual guidance: The layout prioritizes clarity, auditability, and a calm enterprise UI with card-based sections, consistent typography, and accessible controls.

Visual Style (as defined in the project’s design system):
- Color Palette, typography, spacing, and UI element treatments are defined in the user prompt. Follow the exact color tokens and typography scales provided to ensure consistent visual language. The page should align with the “Data Visualization, Card Design, Navigation, Interactive Elements, and Micro-Interactions” guidelines described, including hover states, focus rings, and accessible contrast.
- No connected APIs are required for the MVP beyond presenting the NarrativeEvents and raw payloads, but the UI must be wired to fetch and render data from existing endpoints or mock data during development.

Mandatory Coding Standards — Runtime Safety
CRITICAL: All code must guard against null/undefined values before calling array methods, use Supabase-safe patterns, and initialize state correctly.

- Supabase query results: Always use nullish coalescing — const items = data ?? [].
- Array methods: Never call on a value that could be null/undefined/non-array. Use (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
- React useState for arrays/objects: Initialize with correct type — useState<Type[]>([]).
- API response shapes: Validate — const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
- Optional chaining: Use ?. when accessing nested API/result properties.
- Destructuring with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}.

PROJECT CONTEXT: TARGET PAGE and PLATFORM
- Project: Gbox360 — Investor Perception Index & Narrative Intelligence.
- Data ingestion and canonical narrative model exist. For MVP, you’ll surface a deterministic, rule-based or lightweight-embedding-supported narrative events list, with append-only storage and replay support.
- Authority weights and credibility proxies exist as provisional rules (Analyst > Media > Retail; credibility proxies for management language and repetition).
- End-to-end user flow supports drill-down from Company View into a detailed narrative explanation with exportable artifacts.

API/Data Model assumptions (adjust to your real backend as needed):
- NarrativeEvent:
  - id: string
  - sourcePlatform: string
  - speaker: { name: string, role: string } // role heuristic
  - audienceClass: string
  - rawText: string
  - payload?: object // the raw payload object
  - timestamp: string (ISO 8601)
  - authorityScore: number
  - credibilityFlags: string[] // e.g., ["reliable", "unverified"]
  - provenance?: { documentId: string, url?: string }
- NarrativeSeries or Movement:
  - movementId: string
  - narrativeTitle: string
  - currentIPI: number
  - persistenceScore: number
  - contributionDelta: number
  - events: NarrativeEvent[]
  - calculationInputs?: object
- AuditArtifact:
  - artifactId: string
  - signedAt: string
  - signature: string
  - payloadReferences: string[] // event IDs or payload hashes
  - narrativeSummary: string
  - calculationInputs: object
  - jsonExport: object
  - pdfExport?: Buffer/String (generated on server)

Components to Build
- DrilldownPage: The main page component orchestrating layout, header, event list, raw payload modal, timeline replay, filters, and export actions.
- NarrativeHeaderCard: Displays narrative title, persistence score, contribution, trend indicator; includes a small sparkline or mini-trend stat.
- NarrativeEventsTable: Paginated/virtualized list of NarrativeEvent rows with:
  - sourcePlatform badge
  - speaker name/role
  - audience class
  - timestamp
  - snippet (trimmed rawText)
  - authorityScore display
  - credibility flags indicators
  - viewRawButton to open RawPayloadModal
  - careful null-safety around all fields
- RawPayloadModal: Large modal with tabs:
  - Summary metadata (movementId, narrativeTitle, event count)
  - Raw payload JSON viewer with syntax highlighting (optional)
  - Provenance metadata
  - Download button (payload.json)
- TimelineReplay: Interactive timeline controls with:
  - Play/Pause, Step Forward/Backward
  - Highlighted current event
  - Repetitions/spikes detection visualization
  - Keyboard accessible controls
- FiltersPanel: UI controls for:
  - Source type select (News, Social, Transcript)
  - Authority tier select (Analyst, Media, Retail)
  - Credibility flags toggles
  - Date range picker (start/end)
  - Apply/Reset actions
- AuditExportPanel: Button to trigger export and download of artifacts:
  - Exports JSON + signed PDF
  - Includes event list, narrative summary, weighting parameters, and calculation inputs
- BackToCompanyViewLink: Simple navigation control that preserves context (companyId, window, current IPI).
- DataVizMini: Optional compact visualizations for per-event signaling (e.g., small bars or dots).

Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Routing: Add a route for /drilldown/:movementId or equivalent; ensure Deep linking works with back navigation to Company View.
- State Management:
  - useState with proper types for arrays/objects, initialized to [] or {} as appropriate.
  - useEffect to fetch movement data, events, and calculation inputs; guard with Array.isArray checks and default fallbacks.
  - Local UI state for modals, filters, and timeline playback; default booleans and numeric values handled safely.
- Data Fetching:
  - Use provided API endpoints or mocks to load:
    - Movement metadata (movementId, narrativeTitle, currentIPI, persistenceScore, contributionDelta)
    - Underlying NarrativeEvents (array)
    - Calculation inputs and weighting parameters (object)
  - Always apply null checks and default shapes:
    - const movement = response?.data?.movement ?? {}
    - const events = Array.isArray(response?.data?.events) ? response.data.events : []
- UI Logic:
  - Guard all array operations with (events ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(events) ? events.map(...) : [].
  - Render skeleton/loading states when data is not yet available; avoid crashing on undefined fields.
  - Language: Copy should clearly distinguish between raw payload data, provenance, and calculated inputs.
- Accessibility:
  - All interactive UI elements should be keyboard accessible.
  - Focus styles in #93C5FD per the design guidelines.
  - Color contrast must meet WCAG AA for primary text and controls.
- Security:
  - Do not expose secrets or private keys. The audit artifact signing may occur on server; client should handle signed artifact metadata and securely download signed artifacts.
  - Validate all user-provided inputs (date ranges, filters) on the client side before sending to server; ensure no injection of raw payloads without proper escaping in UI.

### Backend
- Provide or integrate APIs (or ensure existing APIs) for:
  - GET /movements/:movementId to fetch movement metadata.
  - GET /movements/:movementId/events to fetch NarrativeEvents with pagination metadata.
  - POST /movements/:movementId/export-audit to generate a signed artifact for the given filtered view; return a signed artifact URL or blob for JSON and PDF exports.
  - Optional: endpoints to fetch calculationInputs and weighting parameters used for the IPI view.
- Data Validation:
  - Validate response shapes; ensure the server returns objects with the exact fields described above.
  - For events, ensure timestamps are ISO 8601 strings; authorityScore is a number; rawText is present.

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - DrilldownPage requests movement metadata, events, and calculation inputs.
  - NarrativeHeaderCard renders with movement data.
  - NarrativeEventsTable renders events; RawPayloadModal uses event.payload or event.rawText.
  - TimelineReplay consumes events to animate through the sequence; updates currentEventIndex state.
  - AuditExport triggers server-side artifact generation and returns a signed artifact (or a URL to download).
- Error handling:
  - Gracefully handle API failures, show user-friendly error states with retry options.
  - Ensure UI does not crash if results are null or partially missing; implement safe guards around every field access.

## User Experience Flow
1. User opens Drilldown — Why Did This Move? from the Company View (IPI Detail) or directly via a deep link.
2. Page loads: fetch movement metadata, underlying NarrativeEvents, and calculation inputs. Show skeletons/placeholders until data arrives.
3. NarrativeHeaderCard displays narrative title, current IPI, persistence, and delta trend.
4. EventsList presents the underlying NarrativeEvents in a paginated view. Each row shows:
   - Source platform tag
   - Speaker name and role heuristic
   - Audience class
   - Timestamp
   - Snippet of rawText
   - Authority score and credibility flags
   - View Raw button
5. User uses FiltersPanel to narrow results by source type, authority tier, credibility flags, and date range; Apply updates the EventsList and TimelineReplay.
6. User clicks View Raw on an event to open RawPayloadModal, which shows the complete payload with provenance; offers a download option.
7. User uses TimelineReplay to step through events, with current event highlighted; spikes and repetitions are visually indicated.
8. User clicks Audit Export to generate a signed artifact, downloading JSON and PDF exports for audit purposes.
9. User clicks Back to Company View to return to the IPI Detail with context preserved.

## Technical Specifications

Data Models: [Schema details]
- NarrativeEvent
  - id: string
  - movementId: string
  - sourcePlatform: string
  - speaker: { name: string, role: string } | null
  - audienceClass: string | null
  - rawText: string | null
  - payload: object | null
  - timestamp: string | null
  - authorityScore: number
  - credibilityFlags: string[] | null
  - provenance?: { documentId: string, url?: string } | null
- Movement
  - movementId: string
  - narrativeTitle: string
  - currentIPI: number
  - persistenceScore: number
  - contributionDelta: number
  - events?: NarrativeEvent[] | null
  - calculationInputs?: object | null
- AuditArtifact
  - artifactId: string
  - signedAt: string
  - signature: string
  - payloadReferences: string[] // event ids
  - narrativeSummary: string
  - calculationInputs: object
  - jsonExport: object
  - pdfExportUrl?: string

API Endpoints: [Routes and methods]
- GET /movements/:movementId
  - Response: { data: Movement | null, error?: string }
- GET /movements/:movementId/events
  - Query: page, pageSize, filters
  - Response: { data: NarrativeEvent[], page: number, pageSize: number, total: number }
- POST /movements/:movementId/export-audit
  - Body: { includeEvents: string[], includeCalculationInputs: boolean }
  - Response: { artifactUrlJson: string, artifactUrlPdf: string, artifactId: string }
- Optional: GET /movements/:movementId/export-status for long-running jobs

Security: [Authentication, authorization requirements]
- Ensure user is authenticated via existing session/token (JWT or session cookie) for page access.
- Authorization: User must have read access to the company and movement data; ensure role-based access if needed.
- Audit export endpoints should require elevated permissions if artifacts contain sensitive data; sign artifacts server-side and provide verifiable signatures.

Validation: [Input validation rules]
- Filters: Validate date ranges to ensure start <= end; sanitize inputs to prevent injection in query parameters.
- Movement and event IDs: Validate UUID-like or slugs format; guard against undefined IDs.
- API responses: Use Array.isArray for lists; default to [] for null data; ensure essential fields exist before rendering.

Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] The Drilldown page renders without crashes when movement has 0 events; the UI shows empty state but all sections render gracefully.
- [ ] NarrativeEventsTable uses safe (events ?? []).map(...) and displays all fields with proper null checks; the “view raw” button opens RawPayloadModal with payload data.
- [ ] RawPayloadModal loads provenance metadata and offers a download of the raw payload JSON; handles absent payload gracefully.
- [ ] TimelineReplay can advance through the events, highlighting the current event and marking repetitions/spikes; keyboard navigation supported.
- [ ] FiltersPanel correctly filters events by source type, authority tier, credibility flags, and date range; Apply refreshes the list and timeline.
- [ ] Audit Export button triggers server-side artifact generation; downloads for JSON and PDF are offered; artifact includes movement metadata, filtered events, weighting parameters, and calculation inputs.
- [ ] Back to Company View link returns to the Company View with preserved context (companyId and current window) and no data leakage.

UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project’s design system and ensure the page conforms to the Visual Style and Design Philosophy described earlier:
- Use the exact color palette tokens, typography scales, spacing guidelines, and component treatments.
- Maintain hierarchical clarity: Narrative Header at top, followed by the Events list, Raw Payload modal as needed, then the Timeline and Filters, with the Audit Export controls clearly visible.
- Ensure consistent card design, subtle borders, soft shadows, and accessible controls.
- Implement micro-interactions with the described timings (150–220ms hover, 300ms panel transitions) for a polished enterprise feel.

